Sure, here's an example GAMS code for calculating network data envelopment analysis with sample parameter values.

```
Set
    i           'DMU index (including virtual DMU)'      /1*5/,
    j(i)        'Input index'                            /1*2/,
    k(i)        'Output index'                           /1*3/,
    h(i,i)      'Network structure'                      /1.2,1.3,2.4,3.4,4.5/;

Scalar
    bigM        'large number'                            /10000/;

Parameter
    x(i, j)     'Input quantity for each DMU'
                /1.1     10, 1.2     15, 2.1     20, 2.2     25, 3.1     30,
                 3.2     35, 4.1     40, 4.2     45, 5.1     50, 5.2     55/,
    y(i, k)     'Output quantity for each DMU'
                /1.1     3, 1.2     2, 1.3     5, 2.1     8, 2.2     6, 2.3     4,
                 3.1     12, 3.2     10, 3.3     15, 4.1     18, 4.2     16,
                 5.1     24, 5.2     22, 5.3     20/,
    d(i,h,i)    'Distance measure between DMUs'
                /1.2     15, 1.3     20, 2.4     5, 3.4     10, 4.5     25/;

PositiveVariable
    u(i)        'Normalized input weight',
    v(i)        'Normalized output weight',
    s(i)        'Slack variable for input resources',
    r(i)        'Slack variable for output resources',
    z           'Efficiency score';

Variable
    objValue    'Objective value for DEA';

u.up(i) = 1;
v.up(i) = 1;

Equation
    inputResource(i)    'Input resources constraint',
    outputResource(i)   'Output resources constraint',
    efficiency(i)       'Efficiency calculation';

inputResource(i).. sum(j, u(i)*x(i, j)) - s(i) =l= 0;
outputResource(i).. sum(k, v(i)*y(i, k)) - r(i) =g= 0;
efficiency(i).. z =e= sum(h(i,j,k), d(i,h,i)*(u(i)*x(i,j) - u(h(i,j))*x(h(i,j),j))*(v(i)*y(i,k) - v(h(i,k))*y(h(i,k),k))) - sum(u, s(u)) - sum(v, r(v));

Model DEA /all/;

option lp = cplex;

solve DEA maximizing z using lp;

display z.l;
``` 

In this example, there are 5 decision-making units (DMUs), each having 2 inputs and 3 outputs. The distances between the DMUs are also defined. The program calculates the relative efficiencies of the DMUs using the Network Data Envelopment Analysis (NDEA) method. 

The sample parameter values are:
- x(i, j): Input quantity for each DMU
- y(i, k): Output quantity for each DMU
- d(i,h,i): Distance measure between DMUs

The optimization problem is constrained by the input and output resources, as well as the efficiency of each DMU. Outputs display the efficiency score for each DMU. 

Note that this is just an example, and you would need to modify and adapt it to fit your specific problem formulation and data set.

